In Rust, the #[panic_handler] attribute defines the behavior of the panic! macro in #![no_std] environments. Without the standard library, Rust lacks a default panic handler, necessitating the implementation of a custom one. This handler specifies how the program should respond to panics, such as logging the error, halting execution, or performing other actions. 
RUST DOCUMENTATION

Implementing a custom panic handler is essential because #![no_std] applications operate in environments without standard runtime support. The standard library provides default panic handling mechanisms, but these are unavailable in #![no_std] contexts. Therefore, developers must define their own panic handling behavior to ensure the program responds appropriately to unexpected errors. 
RUST EMBEDDED DOCUMENTATION

For example, a simple panic handler that enters an infinite loop can be defined as follows:

rust
Copy code
#![no_std]
use core::panic::PanicInfo;

#[panic_handler]
fn panic(_info: &PanicInfo) -> ! {
    loop {}
}


In this example, the panic function is marked with the #[panic_handler] attribute and enters an infinite loop upon a panic, effectively halting the program. 
